<div style="Font-family: Merriweather">
===<span style="Font-family: Merriweather">Environmental Hazards</span>===
As mentioned earlier, the level's infrastructure is structurally fragile, with certain buildings prone to collapse. Moreover, the air of Level 236 can also be a medical threat if inhaled for prolonged periods, as it is polluted with leftover carbon dioxide, methane, and rotting carcasses. Air purification items like gas masks are highly recommended for travel at this level.
===<span style="Font-family: Merriweather">Auditory Hallucinations</span>===
Sometimes, a wanderer within Level 236 can experience auditory hallucinations of supposedly loud, anguished human screams. According to data analysis, this phenomenon occurs more frequently at night, particularly during the 8:00 PM - 9:00 PM period, and usually lasts 5 to 30 minutes. While not inherently dangerous, it can still cause panic for unsuspecting wanderers.
==<span style="Font-family: Merriweather">Colonies and Outposts</span>==
Level 236 is currently considered No Man's Land after the disaster and the fall of the Church of Sempiternism. It is also being contested by several Groups of Interest, such as the [[M.E.G.]] and the [[Republic of Aurielle]], all seeking to claim/colonize the land for local resource extraction, building habitable communities, and providing a political or military edge.

==<span style="Font-family: Merriweather">Addendums</span>==
Writings from a torn page found in a journal.<br><br><div style="border: 2px solid #FFFFFF; border-radius: 0px; padding: 30px 20px; margin: 5px 10px; color: #FFFFFF; margin-bottom: 20px; overflow: hidden; font-family: Shadows Into Light; font-size: 16px">
'''5th of March, 2008'''
----
I had been wandering the limitless, distorted, unholy environment of The Canvas for weeks on end, slowly hating myself more and more. I hate the fact that I turned left that night while walking on the street. I hate the fact that just from one minor mistake, I'll never see the past life that I've built ever again. I hate the fact that I put myself into this. And I hate the fact that I'm selfish (perhaps foolish) enough to keep wandering and surviving.
<br>

Repetitive, meaningless spaces. It wasn't like walking to a destination. It was like being eternally stuck in a DMV queue, except there was nobody there, forced to confront and fight pale imitations of what was once human. All the survivor groups I joined all fell to the hazards of this dimension, or to their own selfish temptations. I felt hopeless. I felt like I was on the verge of giving up every second I waited, every step I took.

And yet, even in all that darkness, he had saved me.

A charismatic young man in a minimalist white suit approached me while I was sitting on the beige carpets, staring at the lifeless LED lights above. He offered me a loaf of stale bread and a bottle of Almond Water. Not the tastiest thing, but it felt good after days of surviving on rations. He sat down next to me and started discussing great wonders, about the true meaning and purpose of humans here, why The Canvas had chosen us. After so long, I finally felt a spark inside me. A spark of hope, wonder, and warmth, like a loving mother was watching over us.

And he led me to a home. A paradise, you could say. It wasn't flashy or bureaucratic, but natural. It felt like I was on Earth once again, breathing air that's not made from a soulless office. There were people there. They welcomed me with open arms. I finally felt like I was free.

And I finally learned to embrace The Canvas instead of fearing it.
</div>
Handwriting found on a torn page of a pupil's notebook.
