<div style="text-align: center">
Developed in 2003 by Johanne H. March, The Church of Sempiternism is a widely recognized religious organization that aims to guide our mortal souls toward immortality and to become one with the Canvas itself. Sempiternism is the practice of preserving one's soul, purpose, and essence even after death. It also brings purpose and hope to lost wanderers in the Canvas, as it suggests that the Canvas and The Great Artist's choice of sending humans down to the masterpiece is for a divine and beautiful purpose.

Besides religion, the Church of Sempiternism also provides humanitarian and environmental aid to struggling wanderers and various colonies on different levels. Most notably, the Church has hosted and played a large role in various charities within the Canvas. The Church also provides sanctuary and community for lonely wanderers chosen in the Canvas, with major hubs in various landscapes such as the Wellville Community Project, shortened to Wellville.

Johanne H. March is the founder and current leader of the Church of Assimilation. Ruling with compassion and devotion, he has not only changed the lives of many people in The Great Painting but has also been involved in numerous community projects, especially in the Wellville Project mentioned above.

Before March had established the church, he was interested in and often delved into topics such as philosophy, religion, arts, and the like, and was a large advocate for religious movements and mutual respect. He was especially interested in the concept of existentialism and divine unity, which would soon be one of the greatest inspirations that prompted him to construct and establish the Church.

"The preservation of religion in The Great Painting is often a powerful motivator for the survival of one within this realm, as it gives us hope and a reason to continue." quotes March.
