<center><big><big><big>i am the voice of god!</big></big></big></center>

<br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br>
<div style="background: #000000; border: 2px solid #FFFFFF; border-radius: 0px; padding: 30px 20px; margin: 5px 10px; color: #FFFFFF; margin-bottom: 20px; overflow: hidden">
'''FOUND FOOTAGE - RECORDING #1'''
<div style="font-family: Cormorant Garamond; font-size: 16px">
<div class="logo_img hoverimg-dim">
[[File:TALK.png|center|frameless|510px|link=]]
</div>
<br>
You walk into the damp air of the auditorium through the crowd of chattering people, particles, and dust bunnies, hitting your shoes every step you take on the wooden floor. The lights flickered for a while, but ultimately stayed on. It was the usual Sunday meeting hosted by Johanne, where you'd see him talk about the wonders of the Canvas or talk about a great moral problem. It was mandatory to join these meetings the moment you decided to sign up to be a member of the Church. When you first joined, you thought they were a waste of time and that you'd get through these speeches to go home. But then you started to truly see how life-changing this philosophy was. You started to believe. You started to genuinely look forward to these times.

The iconic figure of Johanne illuminated in the auditorium's lights as he stepped up onto the stage. Adjusting his microphone and tie, he greets the entire room with great enthusiasm. One clap echoes through the room, and suddenly, many more fill the auditorium. You also clap until the noise has died down. After a while of silence, Johanne stares down at his script, and his polite and firm voice booms through the microphone.
----

"My children! Look to your left, and now look to your right! What do you see? A fellow human being you resonate with? That spark of recognition? For the first time in years, you're not sharing food with strangers who might betray you at any time. For the first time in years, you've finally felt a sense of family you've yearned for! You are here because you want to escape the sorrow, the starvation, the feeling of loneliness you've felt all this time wandering the Canvas. You want to stop being treated as prey for the entities, and for them to feel insignificant in this dimension, many may call a 'hellhole'.

But we see you, we see your struggles. We understand you. And we've enlightened you. We've shown you what it feels like to be seen, what it feels like to be safe! We can hear that unexplainable ache in your heart or that painful anxiety in the back of your head. They aren't a flaw or a sign of weakness; it's simply your potential, your essence, breaking through the seemingly infinite static and the crushing weight of living in this masterpiece. This world was designed for you, my loyal people! They: the news, your alleged "friends and family", the desperate organizations; they're trying to pull you back into the spiral of hopelessness and insignificance to fuel their own needs! They are simply terrified of the Canvas being finished, and what will inevitably happen after that. But you, my friends, you have been granted the truth, for I am the voice of God! You will be heavily rewarded for your faith—eternity and infinite beauty.

But I shall speak the truth: the path to this reward is a narrow and difficult one. The baggage, the struggles, the pain of your old life will simply not sufficiently fit through this path. They will sink you down when the tide comes, dragging you by the foot like a gold anchor. If you want to see the Truth, follow me, for I am the Truth. Step into the masterpiece with me, and you will be immortalized—forever. 

Praise the Art."
</div></div>

<div style="background: #000000; border: 2px solid #FFFFFF; border-radius: 0px; padding: 30px 20px; margin: 5px 10px; color: #FFFFFF; margin-bottom: 20px; overflow: hidden">
'''FOUND FOOTAGE - RECORDING #2'''
<div class="logo_img hoverimg-dim">
[[File:Screenshot 2026-04-17 204410.png|center|frameless|310px|link=]]
</div><br>
<div style="font-family: Cormorant Garamond; font-size: 16px">
It is a quiet night. The sound of whistling wind fills the atmosphere with melancholy with each step you take on the dirt road. Johanne had ordered everyone to meet up at the town square to celebrate a special outdoor ceremony. Among the crowds of people going along the same path as you, you turn your eyes to Daniel, a friend you've made since you joined this wonderful community. He seemed to notice you as well. You casually greet each other while strolling.

"I wonder what this will be about," Daniel says, wiping his palm on his thighs. "I've heard people say He’s capable of things no one else can explain. That just proves it, doesn't it? It proves his connection, his faith. I don't understand how anyone could see it and think otherwise."

You do a small nod in agreement. "We've seen some of the miracles he's done for us and the world," you mention. "Whatever it is, it will be necessary for our faith. Praise the Art," you add.

Keeping your hands in your jacket's pockets, you and Daniel enter the town square. The atmosphere is peaceful yet lively. The sound of crickets chirping, the wind, and the people beside you chatting and whispering to each other. You can't help but notice the men in vests carrying rifles patrolling the corners of the square. They've always given you a sense of unease with their lack of faces and their statue-like posture, but you shake that thought off. They're only there to protect you from threats, of course.

Johanne calmly walks to the center of the square, carrying a matchbox. He puts the microphone close to his mouth. He clears his throat, and the crowd goes silent. After that, he starts talking.

----
"Welcome back, loyal followers of the Church! The air tonight is quite tranquil, yes... I am here to take a step further and guide you to enlightenment. As I've said, your past life is dragging you down, stagnating your potential. Your old skin needs to be shed to be able to see the truth. And I've called you, all of you, here today to do exactly that. I will help you shed your old skin. Do not worry, the process will not hurt. You will feel much lighter after it. Much more free.

Come forth, bring items that remind you of your past, flawed history, and annihilate it. Praise the Art."
----

Johanne lights a match and drops it in a bonfire. Suddenly, glowing flames burst to life, illuminating the darkness more than the lights ever did. Johanne's white suit glows orange in the firelight.

You bring out your phone and M.E.G. employee badge. You've earned that badge after working grueling hours with those guys in bureaucratic offices, seeing your comrades die to unspeakable horrors. They weren't worthy anyway. The memories of those times will die soon as the flames rage. Yet you're not sure how to feel about it.

Seven lines of people neatly form around the bonfire. A woman sobs as she throws her daughter's teddy bear into the fireplace. One of the men in a vest places his hand on her shoulder, but it feels more like a restraint than comforting. It is your turn. You sigh as you throw your phone and badge. As you walk away, you turn back to the sight of them being engulfed in flames, along with many other items.

Praise the Art.
</div></div>
<div style="background: #000000; border: 2px solid #FFFFFF; border-radius: 0px; padding: 30px 20px; margin: 5px 10px; color: #FFFFFF; margin-bottom: 20px; overflow: hidden">
'''FOUND FOOTAGE - RECORDING #3'''
<div style="font-family: Cormorant Garamond; font-size: 16px">
<div class="logo_img hoverimg-dim">
[[File:Screenshot 2026-04-17 220723.png|center|430px|frameless|link=]]
</div>
<br>
"My children, welcome back! Shall we forever sing the hymns of righteousness, of worthiness! But alas, I'm getting older and weaker by the day, and I'm here today to tell you my final message, and possibly the Church's final message ever, too. The ascension shall happen on the night of March, next week. Some of you may be unprepared, some may even feel scared, but don't worry. It will be painless and beautiful.

Look at your very hands, look at the scars on your palm. They are imperfections. They are like a smudge on the Canvas. Life, as we call it, is simply a rough draft. We wander these infinite landscapes like unfinished thoughts. But the Artist will perfect our form. He is almost done, and what's left will be pure bliss as many generations look up to you, look up to your beauty, your eternity. You are the ones who will make the Church's legacy remain, even if we don't physically exist.

We'll finally be free, free from the tyrannical grasp of those residing in the beautiful Canvas. Lately, external groups have been threatening our fundamental stability. They told me that we were stealing their members. They told me we were stealing their glory. But they're all lying to you! They just want to justify pulling people into the darkness and brainwashing those people! They are trying to hide the Truth from you.

Do you remember what happened to the people who disappeared? They didn't leave; they were kidnapped by those who claimed to keep the peace. They were told their faith was a sickness. They're already sharpening their sticks and their stones to kick down our castle of faith! Well, we shall let them come! Let them see that we are not a sickness, but the cure! I will save all of you, and what's left will be eternal emptiness and loneliness on their part! Together, will prevail onwards and finally achieve what we were destined to achieve!

Praise the Art."
</div></div>

<div style="background: #000000; border: 2px solid #FFFFFF; border-radius: 0px; padding: 30px 20px; margin: 5px 10px; color: #FFFFFF; margin-bottom: 20px; overflow: hidden">
'''FOUND FOOTAGE - RECORDING #4'''
<div style="font-family: Cormorant Garamond; font-size: 16px">
<div class="logo_img hoverimg-dim">
[[File:BURNFALL2.png|center|frameless|490px|link=]]
</div>
<br>
They claimed it was revolutionary, that they would achieve the ultimate goal they've been yearning for this entire time, and that the Artist had finally met them with their loyalty and granted them the ultimate gift. They claimed that they'd finally be immortal, that they'd finally be assimilated. And that this act would also bring an end to this pointless suffering.

The day came. Radios and sirens blared through the fields, urging people to enter the town hall. Multiple jeeps that looked more like barely functional, camouflaged cars, surrounded the border as men in outdated vests and gas masks, carrying fully-loaded rifles, got out of the vehicles. Some menacingly stood there, as if guarding and overseeing whatever operations there were, and some were ordered to run into the village.

The people looked back. The smell of black smoke and gasoline suffocated them. The houses, the churches, the schools—barely noticeable as the fire raged and the fumes became more insufferable. As they burned, their faces crisp, horror, so did the memories. Water in them evaporated, eyelids closed, encased dried-out spheres. And yet, the radio continued spewing out words of encouragement and fearlessness, but it was simply white noise now.

Some tried to escape, trying to save what was left of their lives. They were gunned down immediately. Their spinal columns, brains, and neurons exploded into red mist as the lead punctured their bodies, thought brought to an end, blood indiscernible from the wild flames. Those who did successfully escape died in the smoke or flames. Their lungs weren’t made to be irrigated by ashen air. 

Such a scenery would have touched god’s heart, if they had. Theirs were to be consumed in the hecatomb. They were to feel horrified by overexcited nerves, which would soon be exposed to thick air. The thick air censored their agony and smoked the city's cement, wood, and concrete with a scent of decay.

Praise the Art.
